{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"71d4551b-7bbe-49ac-bdfc-f910daa0787f","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2**, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    // TestContext is injected automatically via constructor (MSTest 3.2+)\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; init; }\n\n    // Synchronous init — runs before each test\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // sync setup work\n    }\n\n    // Async init — runs before each test (after sync init)\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup work\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`TestContext`** — declare a `public TestContext TestContext { get; init; }` property. MSTest injects it automatically (no `[TestContext]` attribute needed in v3+, though it still works).\n- **Sync init** — use `[TestInitialize]` on a `void` method.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize]` on a `Task`-returning method. You can have **both** on the same class; sync runs first.\n- For **class-level** one-time setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static) and its async variant similarly.\n\nWant me to scaffold a test file with this pattern?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1d55742-c63f-4438-97a7-582f7a6d26f6","outputTokens":357},"id":"2c60990a-f587-4aa0-8162-b243be4da519","timestamp":"2026-04-03T03:29:36.249Z","parentId":"7c3b0962-561c-4d42-9ae2-209598185a9b"}
